{"/service/ndnp/wvu/batch_wvu_garbo_ver02/data/sn86092280/00517011216/1921020901/0126.xml":{"full_text":"__2>\nThe People\nLook to this pa per\nfor world news,\nand your ad for\nstore news. What's\nyour news today? j\nADVERTISE i\nThe Elkins InterJUountain\nMEMBER ASSOCIATED PRESS\nWeather\nForecast\nFAIR\nVOLUMEJUV. >0. Ill\nr\u2014\u25a0\u25a0\nTHE ELKINS INTER-MOUNTAIN. WEDNESDAY. FEBRUARY 9. 1921\nTHREE CENTS I*EK COPY\n'__ 1,111 s\nSHALL UNION\nMEN SERVE ON\nMATEWAN JURY?\nDetermination to Settle the Question\nfor All Time Forcibly Impressed\nin Court\nMOtlON TO STRIKE ALL\nUNION MEN FROM JURY\n(By Associated Press.)\nWILLIAMSON. W. VA., Feb. 9.\u2014A\nreport widely eirrulated here this\nafternoon that Judge R. D. Bailey\nwould rule that trade unionists would\nnot he permitted to serve as juroros to\ntry the 21 Matewan battle defendants\nwras unauthorized by the court. Judge\nBailey declared that his decision would\ns\u00abot be announced until tomorrow morn\ning and that any rumor concerning the\nnature of his ruling should be dis\ncounted.\nIn the meantime counsel for both\nsides marked time trying to anticipate\nthe court\u2019s decision regulating their\nprocrtlure during the day\u2019s sitting by\ntheir speculation.\n(By Associated Press.)\nWILLIAMSON. W. VA.. Feb. it.\u2014I\u00bbe\ntermination of the state to settle for\nail time whether union labor men are\nto rind places on the jury which is to\n\u2022try the 21 men accused in the Matewan\n^shooting cases was forcibly impressed\non everyone in court this morning.\nInstead of proceeding at once with the\ntask of selecting the jury counsel for\nthe state began vailing witnesses in\nsupr/ t of its motion that all union\nmen be stricken from the tentative\njury panel. Those who have followed\nthe ease closely have been able to place\nbut two of the tentative jurors in this\nclass.\nWith the exceptions of the defend\nants and the opposing counsel less than\n20 persons wore present when court\nopened. Judge Bailey listened with\nclosest attention to the examination of\nthe witnesses after they were called.\nLATE BULLETINS\n(By Associated Press.)\nWASHINGTON'. Feb. ft.\u2014Charges\nthat government bureaus having to do\nwith soldier relief are \u2018\u2022packing the\ncommittees of the American Legion\nwith Bureau employes who are mem\nbers of the Legion\u201d were made before\nthe Legion\u2019s Executive Committee\nhere .today by Abel Davis of Chicago,\nchairman of the hospitalization com-1\nmittoe.\n\"As a result the work of the Legion\nin soldier relief matters is being great\nly handicapped\u201d said Mr. Davis, who1\nadded that at the Cleveland conven-j\ntion \"the bureaus licked us to a frazzle.\nin all matters relating to veteran relief j\nand the Legion wondered how it was\ndone.\u201d\nAfter hearing Mr. Davis the exeeu-j\ntire committee recommended to the\nstate divisions of the Legion that they\nrefrain from appointing government\nbureau employes on their committees.\nFormer service meii are being kept j\nin private hospitals that are indescrib-,\nably tilthly and in conditions that are\nterrible, said Mr. Davis who ''charged\nthat after the men were placed in such\nhospitals they were left without visit\nor inspection of representatives of the\nPublic Health Service. He read a re\nport of a survey of a hospital in Illi\nnois made by representatives of the\nLegion. This said that white &nd\nnegro patients slept in the some room,\nthat the pharmacy containing nam^ies\nand drugs of all sorts was left unlock\ned and that when asked if the male\npatients uped the same bath room as\nthe females the doctor in charge stated\nthat \"the women only remained about\ntwo weeks at a time and didn\u2019t take\nany baths.\"\nThe service men are now being re\nmoved from this hospital Mr. Davis\nsaid as a result of pressure brought to\nbear on public health officials.\n(By Associated Press.)\nPITTSBURG, KAS., Feb. 9.\u2014Miners\nreturned to work today at one of two\nmines affected by a walkout yesterday\nin protest against the arrest of Alex\nander powat. district miner\u2019s presi\ndent and other union officers for con\ntempt of court.\nV\nDAVIS ELKINS\nTRIMS GLENVILLE\nLOCAL COLLEGIANS WIN HARD\nFOUGHT GAME FROM NORMAL- j\nITES BY A SCORE OF 43 TO 23 j\nPa vis a:mI Elkins College won over\nGlenville Normal here Tuesday night\nby the s<-ore of 43-22. Tin* first half\nwas very close ending 14-11 in favor\nof the Collegians. The 'Normalites\ntook the lead early in the game but\nMovie and Elkins overhauled them\ntoward the end of the half and were\nnever in danger afterward.\nFV>r the Normal team C. Wilfong and\nHardman were the bright lights.\nHardman played a brilliant floor game\nfind Wilfong made some very difficult\nshots. For Davis and Elkins Isiftdin\nwas the star offensive man. scoring no\nless than nine field goals. Captain\nYokuni played the best floor game seen\nhere for some time and tied Loiulin for\nHeld goal honors. Daniels made two\ngoals from the middle of the floor and\nhis running mate. Xewcome, held the\nGlenvillites from the basket.\nThe game was sljiw and rather rough\nin the first half but the second was fast\nwith some of the best passing by D.\nand E. that has been seen in Elkins for\nyears.\nLineup and summary:\nGlenville 22 Davis-Elkins 43\nC. Wilfong.. F ....Loudiu\nHardman. F .Trout\n(1. Heed. C .Yokum\njl{. Heed..\u2019.G .Newcome\nStarcher. G .!.Daniels\nj Substitutions: Glenville\u2014< Wil\n,fopg for It. Reed: Davis Elkins\u2014\nl Keyset- for Trout.\nI Field goals\u2014Loudiu ft. Yokum 0.\nj Daniels 2. Wilfong 4. Hardman 1, Reed\n2\nFouls\u2014Hardman fi out of 11; Dan\niels 3 out of 7; Loiulin none out of 3.\nReferee\u2014Xallen. Mt. St. Josephs.\nDIVIDEND OF $1.00 A SHARE\n(By Associated Press.)\nNEW YORK. Feb. 9.\u2014The Standard\nOil Company of Indiana today declar\ned a quarterly dividend of $1 a share,\nI payable March 13 to stockholders of\nirecord February 15. This dividend is\nthe first to be declared on the new $25\u2019\npar stock. 1\n(By Associated Press.)\nMARTI NSBCRG, W. VA\u201e Feb. 9.\u2014\nGarfield Miller, a taxicab driver, of\nHagerstown. Md\u201e was found dead\nearly today near Falling Waters, with\na bullet hole behind his right ear and\nhis neck broken. The money which\nlit* had received in fares also was miss\ning.\nAn automobile which Miller used in\nbis business was found on a roadside\nby Hugh Kreps of Chambersburg, I\u2019a.,\nand- brought to this city. The authori\nties here expressed the opinion tliht\nMiller had been murdered by a pas\nsenger and then robbed.\n(By Associated Press.)\nTI'LSA. OKIiA.. Feb. it.\u20141The Sin\nclair Oil Gas Co. cut the price of\nmid-continent crude oil 2o cents here\ntoday making the quotation $1.7.\"* a\nbarrel.\nThe Prairie (til Gas Co. announced\na similar reduction would be made.\nBoth eonerns announced that curtail\nment of runs put in effect in December\nwould be maintained. The Prairie Co.\nis accepting 70 per cent of oil offered\nand the Sinclair Co. JiO per cent. The\nremainder is stored by the company.\n(By Associated Press.)\nNEW SMYRNA, FLA., Feb. it\nAbandoning preparations to return at\nonce to St. Augustine by rail President\nelect Harding decided today to con\ntinue his vacation a little longer when\nhis house boat, the Victoria, was re-*\nHeated from the mudbank in Mosquito\nLagoon, where she hung up Monday.\nWith the President-elect on l>oard the\nVictoria passed Oak Hills shortly lie\nfore noon and should be aliove Ormond\ntdhlght.\n(By Associated Press.)\nWASHINGTON, Feb. 9.\u2014By direc\ntion of his government Leslie (,'raigie,\nBritish charge here called today on\nSecretary Colby at the State Depart\nment to formally deny published re\nports that officials of the British for\neign office had told American newspap\ner correspondents In London that\nGreat Britain and America were tread\nthe path leading to war.\nThousands Of Men Are Now Idle\nThroughout State of West Virginia\nStale Commissioner of labor Mont-1\ngomery Receives Replies from,\nQuestionnaire* Sent to 180 Firms\nTARIFF Ql'KSTION\nNOT A DEAD ISSI K\n(l!y Associated Press.)\nCHARLESTON. W. VA\u201e Kel*.\nThousands <>f men throughout West!\nVirginia are idle or working on short'\ntime according to answers just r\u00bb*eeiv\n[eil hv the State P.ttreau of labor from,\nISO plants employing lot) persons or\nmore. The answers are in reply to\nMiicstinninires sent out by Samuel li.\nMontgomery. Commissioner of labor,\nto establishments from which he re\nceive.! reports of labor conditions on\nFebruary 1. l'.lL\u2019i.\nPercentage of decrease of employ\nment in various industries follows:\nClassware 4'J. iron and steel 51, lum-J\nher and planing mills SI, pottery and1\nhinaware 10, chemicals and b.v-pro- j\nduets 04. leather and rubber goods lib,,\nbrick and cement 77. clothing products\n-4. railway shops 15. Tobacco and\nI\nstogie lactones showed ail increase in!\nemployment of 1 per cent. j\nThe\" greatest percentage of unem-l\nSTRIKE TEMPEST\nIN A TEAPOT\nREPORTED TROUBLE AT BROAD\nDUS COLLEGE OVER WEARING\nSWEATERS EXAGGERATED\n(By Associated Press.)\nCLARKSBURG. W. VA., Feb. D.\u2014\nThe reported strike of students at\nBroddaus College, the state Baptist de\nnominational institution at IMiilippi\never an order against the wearing of\nsweaters is characterized by trustees\nand faculty members as a \u201cmere\ntempest in a teapot.\"\nThe order issued by President\nIiulley, directed young men students\nnot to appear without coats or in\nsweaters in chapel, classrooms, lobby\nor dining rooms, the reason therefor\nbeing to inculcate good manners, it\nbeing considered not good form to ap\npear without coats in such places in\nthe presence of young women. It has\ni boon the custom at the institution and\ntin* college authorities are disposed to\nenforce the ruling.\ni After the order had been issued five\n[students appeared in chapel wearing\nsweaters and were subjected to dis\ncipline, but all these are now pursuing\ntheir studies. There has been no\nstrike although there is talk 'amoug I\nsome students that they may refuse to\nreturn to the college at the end of the\npresent semester and will, finish their\nstudies at some other college. The\ncollege authorities believe nothing will\ncome of this and that the situation will\nadjust itself In favor of the usual col\nlege authority and discipline.\nPresbyterian C. 7J. Social Friday\nnext at the \"Y\u201d ai 7:45. A silver\noffering will be asked. 2-8-2t\nI\nploy men t is in lln> glass, iron, .stool,\nchemical. lmnlior. tniililing matorial.\nloatlior, rubber unit clothing Industries.\nSeventeen oonoorns reported wugo\nmined Ions from o to per oont, while\ntlvo that had boon paying honusos have\nsuspended tlioni.\nForty-nine firms roportod Unit they,\nhad mado no rodnolons in wages and\nthat they did not export any redue-!\ntions, wliilo 12 answers wore eondi\ntional.\ntins shortage, soareity of orders and\na goJioral slump in business were the\nreasons assigned to the rednetion of\nt!ii\u2018 number of employes, while the re\nduction in wages according to one con\ncern \u201cwill depend on the men them\nselves.\" Some of our men turn out a\nfair day's work while others seem to\nhave fallen into a rut and want to do\nas little as possible, it so added.\n\u201cA number of managers report that\nthey are looking on the bright side lint\nthe survey which is ns comprehensive I\nas it is accurate is not very encourag\ning.\" Commissioner Montgomery said.\n\u201cThis becomes more evident when one\nremembers the number of coal mines\nUnit are idle and the thousands of mine\nworkers that are out of employment.\"\n\u201cThis report on the business outlook\nreflects the opinion of the best minds\nHARBINGER\nOF SPRING\nTHUNDER AND RAIN STORM\nSERVES AS PLEASANT REMIND\nER THAT *SPRING IS HERE\nHave you Keen a cardinal yet?\nHave you heard the robin sing? Have\nyou had your till of ramps as yet?\nHas the sap begun to rise in the\nmaple? Since the warm rain and\nthunderstorm of Tuesday night such\nquestions are on the lips of our people.\nDespite the fact that the calendar is.\nunwilling to give the reason any ad-'\nvance standing, insisting stubbornly\ntiiat it is not yet the middle of Help-n\nary. nature seems inclined to thrust\nspring upon 11s.\nThe thunderstorm and rain were not\nlocal, but were part of a general storm\narea .that covers this and adjoining\nstates. It begun here about 2:30 A.\nM., and for an hour or more there were\na series of quite heavy daps. A busi\nness man was startled out of his sleep,\nthinking that the vault at one of the\nbanks must have been blown up. An\nex-service man who saw the real thing\nin cannonading in France was awaken\ned with a dreamy feeling that the Ger\nmans were making another raid, and\nhe crawled under his blankets and\nwent calmly to sleep.\nSo far as has been learned there was\nno damage from the electrical storm\nin this vicinity. It was rather enjoy\ned by all, and serves as a pleasant re\nminder that springtime with its wrarm\nrains, thunderstorms, birds and flowers\nis not far away.\nAMERICAN LEGION MEETING\nRegular monthly meeting of H. W.\nDaniels Post. American Legion, will\nbe held in Rotary Club Rooms, Elkins,\nIV. Va\u201e on February 10, 1021. at 7:30\np. m. 2-8-3t\nOUR FINAL CLEAN-UP OF\nMEN\u2019S HATS\n3 SPECIAL LOTS\nOdd Lots at $1.95\nOdd Lots at $2.95\nOdd Lots at $4.95\nMany of these at price or less and are very\nSpecial Values\nFOR OUR FINAL CLEAN-UP\nTHE JOHN B. WILT CO.\n\u2022THE STORE WITH A CONSCIENCE*\u2019\nWilt\u2019s Comet Elkins, W. V\u00bbT\n____=\nIn all branches of business,\" ho eon-j\ntinned. \"Several conclusions nia.v ho\ndrawn. One is that the tariff is not aj\ndead issue, and that tin1 conservation\nof gas is a very live Issue, on with\nwhich the future legislatures and ap\nplicants for office will have to deal if\ntin* Steptoe lull is finally held to he\nnnconstitnt ional.\"\n\"Wage reductions a vent Be 20 per\ncent\" said Commissioner Montgomery\nin conclusion, \"while during the same\nperiod the cost of living has boon re\nduced 5 per cent.\"\n\"The glass and chemical industries\"\nMr. Montgomery said \u201cindicated that\ntheir business,- wotdd improve later In\nthe year particularly if imports are im\nproved. The glass men as a rule sug\ngested a higher tariff for protection\nagainst cheaper foreign products.\"\nOnc*glass company Mr. Montgom\nery said, reported that, the business\noutlook depends on the1 disposition of\nthe Steptoe net, the constitutionality\nof which is now being tested in the Su\npreme Court of the United States.\n\u201cIf we are permitted to use our own\ngas in West Virginia,\" lhe company\nreported we will he in good condition,\notherwise we will have to make our\nplans over or go out of business. The\nlumber industry sent In reports indi\ncating a general improvement.\nBIG ROTARY\nCLUB BANQUET\nANNUAL CONFERENCE OF SIXTH\nDISTRICT MAY ItE HEED IN\nRILEY SUNDAY TAIIERNACEE\nFAIRMONT, VV. VA.. Felt. There\nis h possibility Unit the banquet which\nwill he the principal social feature next\nmonth In this city of tlie annual con\nference of Rotary ciuhs of the Sixth\ncjistrict, which covers western Penn\nsylvania and the, state of .West Vir\nginia, will tuke place in the tnber\niuiele now in use for revival meetings\nconducted hy Rev. Rllly Sunday. The\nSunday campaign will come to an end\nSunday and builders Say that the\ntabernacle can be remodeled fpr the\nuse of the Rotarian without much\ntrouble.\nIndications are that fully 1,000 peo\nple from all over the district will be\npresent at the conference. Some of\nthe Pennsylvania clubs have already\nmade reservations and one or two of\nthe clubs from the southern end of\nWest Virginia are making arrange\nments to live in their Pullman cars\nwhich can be purked close to the cen\nter of the city. The local and district\ncommittees are now at work on pro\ngram details, and Fairmont people gen\nerally are prepurlng to make the social\nside of the affair the most cordial and\ncomfortable In the history of the dis\ntrict. Especial efforts are to be made\nto entertain the wives and daughters\nof Rotarians.\nMAIN STREET CHURCH\nRev. John R. Clark of West Union,\nW. Va., will preach at the Main Street\nChristian Church Friday night at 7:30.\nThere will be baptizing also. Every\nitod.v is Invited. 2-9-3t.\nSPECIAL!\nJust received a bar\ngain in \"Ladies\u2019 Dress\nSkirts. Plain and ac\ncordian pleated, mix\ned and all wool serges\nSpecial Prices\n5 Skirts.$2.98\n8 Skirts.$4.98\n$12 Skirts .$6.95\nWHEN YOU BUY OF US\u2014YOU\nBUY RIGHT\nElkins Bargain House:\nL. Goldborg, Prop.1-\n119-21 3rd St. Elkuu, W. Vi.\nPITTSBURG\nGIRL KILLED\nj BY BURGLARS\n117-Year-Old Pauline Oold Found l)md\nIn Red After Robbers Visit\nGold Home\nRESIDENCE NEXT\nDOOR ALSO RORRRD\nBy Associated Press.)\n1MTTS1UHO, PA.. Feb. ft.\u2014Pauline\nGold, uged 17, was found dead in bed\ntoday by her mother, Mrs. Bessie Gold,\nw ho was making an inventory of their\nhome which had been visited by burg\nlars.\nAccording to memhbrs of the Gold\nfamily, Mendel Gold, father of the girl\nawakened early tills morning and\nreached for his trousers to get. a pack\nage of cigarettes. The trousers which\ncontained a note for $r>00 and $S in\ncash were missing.\nHe became alarmed and went down\nstairs and found that a window had\nbeen opened.\n(Sold aroused other members of tho\nfamily mid they found the girl dead in\nbed with linger prints deeply impress*\ned on her throat.\nAccording to morgue physicians the\ngirl was choked to death. The resi\ndence next door to the one occupied by\nthe (Sold family Was also entered and\n#1H0 In cash taken.\nADDRKSH AT HIGH\nSCHOOL AI'DITORIUM\nArrangements have been made for a\nmeeting of the citizens of Elkins to be\nheld at the High School Auditorium on\nThursday evening at 7 o'clock.\nThe local committee In charge of or\ngan!/.at ion have been fortunate in get\nting the services of Mr. William Blake\nwho Is manager of the Cumberland\nChamber of Commerce to outline a\nplan of building np a city.\nAll persons who are Interested in the\nfuture of Elkins should arrange td bp\npresent. Mr. Itlake Is said to 'be one\nof the best talkers and organizers in \u00bb,S\nthis particular line of business in the\ncountry and the time spent to hear him\nwill be well spent. f\nCumberland has made a great suc\ncess with the Chamber of Commerce\nand we want to IIml out why other\ntowns grow*\nThere will be no charge and the peo\nple of Elkins and surrounding country\nare invited to attend.\nIMMIGRATION KILL\nIS DISAPPROVE!!\nWASHINGTON, Feb. It\u2014The House\nImmigration bill which would have\nvirtually stopped immigration for one\nyear was disapproved today by the\nSenate Immigration Committee by a\nvote of 5 to 4. The committee agreed\nto adopt a substitute measure tomor\nrow restricting Immigration on a per\ncentage basis.\nTROOPERS ARRIVE\nAT ALBANY. N. Y.\nBy Associated Press.)\nALBANY. N. Y.. Feb. 0.\u2014State\ntroopers ordered here by Gov. Miller,\nbegan arriving today to assist the\npolice of this city and surrounding\ncommunities during the strike of 1200\nemployes of the I'nited Traction Co.\nTrolley wires torn down by strike sym\npathizers injured plans of the company\nfor resumption of service in this city.\nCOMING!\nFEBRUARY 9-10\nANITA STEWART\nin\n\u201cHER KINGDOM 4\nOF DREAMS\u2019\u2019,\nThe greatest All-Star\nCast in the history of\nthe Photo Play\nBuy your tickets at\none ef the Drug","height":"29528","width":"20232"}}
